She flipped to an empty page and wrote down the date. Below it, she wrote "11.5.648–13.12.648".
"Are you bringing up old memories?" Ivory asked, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? There are only a few days left."
Kari tapped twice on the lantern. "No," as Ivory had expected. The Ice King never let Kari out, as he considered her a "flaw." She was born deaf and was the only daughter in the family, her siblings were all boys.
The same was true for Ivory. When Ivory came out as non-binary, it seemed as if the world was changing. As punishment for this uniqueness, Ivory was given tasks where she spent most of her time alone.
In addition, Ivory was forced to serve the princess. However, it didn't bother Ivory much, as she also gained a friend.
"You're having your birthday soon, right?" Ivory asked, thinking about the fact that the princess was having her birthday in a few days. Kari nodded with a sad flicker in her bright blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate your birthday?" Ivory asked, thinking about the last time the princess answered this question.
"No," Kari tapped. Ivory knew this was a difficult topic for her. Her birthday was the day she was locked in this room and her mother was banished. Ivory had been a baby at that time, but she remembered how upset the servants and the people of the city had been. Ivory had heard that Eirwen was a popular queen. And that she strangely could predict things that later actually happened.
"Well, what do you want to do?" Ivory asked. Kari looked at Ivory excitedly. She was holding a piece of paper in her hand. On it was written:
15 x 15 cm canvas
White, various shades of blue
Brushes in six different sizes
Easel
"These things should I get for you?" Ivory turned to the silent princess, whose braids swayed back and forth from her vigorous tapping. "Yes?" Ivory giggled softly. The usually reserved princess showed so much enthusiasm. It was the first time she had asked about something that had nothing to do with books and came from outside her room.
"Okay! Let's see each other later?" Ivory asked, stood up, and wove through the chaos of paper and notebooks.
Kari nodded, turned back to her notes, and wrapped herself in her blanket.
Ivory left the room, relieved that the princess had finally stepped out of her comfort zone and asked for things beyond her reach, like Malfarben.
Ivory ran through the corridors again and tried to ignore the chatter of the servants.
"I've heard she's supposed to be possessed by Queen Eirwen and therefore goes into this room again and again."
"I've heard she eats children in this room."
"She looks like a man, that's not normal?"
Ivory covered her ears because she couldn't ignore the gossip any longer, and she continued walking. The room of the royal painter was located in the east wing, behind the second door on the left side.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as beautifully decorated as Kari's door. On it was the White Dragon, one of the six primordial dragons said to have supposedly created Frostfell. For a history-loving painter, the White Dragon on the door made perfect sense.
Ivory opened the door and expected the usual mess. Paint splatters everywhere, brushes and paper scattered throughout the room, easels covering every inch of the wall. Unexpectedly, a different scene presented itself. The entire room was clean, and against a red velvet background stood a chair. On the chair sat Crown Prince Aquilo, who was being painted.
"Good morning, Ivory! Would you like to watch as your future king is painted?" asked Aquilo and winked at Ivory.
"Excuse me, little prince," said Ivory, mostly ignoring him and gathering the things the silent princess wanted. "I'm only here to get art supplies."
"My little girl wants to go already?" asked Aquilo. "But I want you to stay!"
"I don't want to stay." Ivory found the art supplies on the list and put them in a box. "Besides, I'm not a girl."
The prince, however, had a different opinion. "Oh sweetie, this is just a phase! As you grow older, you'll grow out of it!" he said vaguely.
"I have to go," said Ivory and felt uncomfortable with the prince's answer. All the nasty comments that he and others had made about Ivory's gender identity in the past came flooding back. I just want to get out of here.
"Are you leaving already?" Suddenly, the prince appeared at the door and ignored the loud protests of the royal painter.
"That's not behavior for a future king!" said Ivory.
"No one will find out. People won't believe you, and the painter will stay quiet if his life is worth anything." He briefly looked at the painter and then leaned closer to Ivory. "What do you think about a date?" Ivory had been harassed before, but never by a prince, let alone the crown prince.
"Do you even know what the word 'No' means?" Ivory spat out and pushed the crown prince away.
"No," answered Aquilo with a smile. Of course, the crown prince, who can have anything he wants, doesn't know what the word "No" means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want to go out with someone like me? You must have at least 100 admirers?"
"Actually, it's 50," he interrupted Ivory, still smiling. He threw his hair back, which whirled in the cold air.
"Now get it! Why me? I'm a danger to the palace." Ivory crossed her arms.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo lifted Ivory's chin with his finger and forced her to look at him.
